TextBlock.TextLine: London Henry Maynard
Antwerp 3 sber 1681
S my last to you, was on the 26 th past sence reds yod of 28 ditto nith
invoyce of 3 packes which you hoped to got aboard cramp I gould with
N50 was because that comp the fine spanisch cloathes which I want my
you may frely bay a bale more assorted as N50 though not se many so
for the bale NN45 is almost told I most of N50 by the past I obferve uh
you say asto the reds too truly the last bale proves deare enough sow
must desist in thout com I hope the last bought are of a more
libely cullour for the formans are so brawne, that I kan not o
then off as for the 6 silver mark the Jesuits here make heavy
complaints of the last recd bleng to then by much, so that they desire
mee to in order non more of that qualite for they conty bat the
same wieght as the formans of 35 a 36 yd: & that which these are
longer I should be milled nto give them due substance, where fore
pray yet his cloathes as formerly he is used to make them & then let
mee have 5 a 10 more by christmas, so to proceed about 5 pr by aven even
3 monthes I doutte he putts the refisall apon you: I would faice pleas
the good peonl: here, for they are a sure iustonce & of consiquanc
there fon endiavoir to provoile on the maker & am ture if he mans
no bester of ofhes they shall nod be sold here, but in case heet shall
befored to gott cloth nor made here of that custome if you ncet 5
pack whites of about 26„ 27 a 30 the 3 fran send themto neces as as yoo
sapose pennien oths, for beleave, I shall sell more pack whites
then yetwer I did I hope the goods in order by pindar wil come
in tmme to come nih him al that good care & la betaken foo al thoey
mee werckly to have had mistakes in the goods arrived with smet,
amonghst which I foand of yd fendingh severall packes with my
march & yett goodds drrecsed to as hop seeper here traly I tought you
would serve no shopkeepers & so to make then accquainted so whers sort
of goods I demand how would you have mee accquant you of then thes
de well in the morth, to be served by if soldonny, I ane bure, to bring
up abird to pak out my cownebys yett let nue have 30 kerseis 33 a 34
yds of the vere best oed lust & the bradest fort no wors then these of 481
last ƒ reds besides one bale of bayes afford from 36 to 46 ƒ8 on which depon
dangh the kersies 23 a 34yd to of 45 a 46 ¾ of ayd and 5 a 6 enches bron
off ayd af least remain
london A brm vivian
8 sence my last to you of 29th past recd yd of 18 ditto yd bill I shall
accent, & hope you wille nort be so argent as to pres for£200 per month
butt make it pronortinable to the months of sall to do all to each others
content t I hope to farnish you with the need full for my att by this
there is no like sgood hood of en oising lett al the inordered goods
bee ready by pindar, & let ma have no mon encusses, for if nou you
were here es or smith you I doubt wee should scbuldes a day or too, a
for I have the best op portunitie of the world world to sell goods not
al the last bayes & cloathes recd: by fith beeng sold butt sea, so then
must be no les then 50 or 60 bajes by pindar, besides what a sent
to rosterdam, of which I heare not one word lett mee know p nent
about what time pindar is to saile, and acquaint mee of all what passe
I finde yd nee man will not do a mis his preffing fouldingh & toullet
fir fing is oather better then that of potter bat mee thinks potter
cloathes are more pleasant it I finde it not in advised to the herw some
what more, shale meafare these cloathes & se hou they hold ont ad vis
ny you whust remain
